#### Example RPC usage


```
let n = 0
let f = () => n++;

//node n2 is creating a new service, uService, on n1
//r1 is the destination, m1 is the source, (e,v) => ... is the callback for node

let r1 = { node: n1, service: "routes", method: 'put'};
//This is sending the RPC stub for 'uService' to n1
let m1 = [{do: util.wire.createRPC(util.wire.toAsync(f))}, 'uService']

//Down the line, n2 will ask n1 to perform the method 'do' on 'uService'
//This will cause node n1 to run f() on node n2 via the RPC stub. 'do' relates to f() because it is defined as a remote function in m1. Why is 'uService' necessary?
//It seems that m2 is meant to be filled with the contents of 'do'?

local.comm.send(m1, r1, (e, v) => {
	let r2 = {node: n1, service: 'uService', method: 'do'};
	let m2 = [];
	local.comm.send(m2, r2, (error, result) => {})
});
```

"well known registry service" called routes, asks n1 to install something.
The payload to the registry call is m1: `[{do: util.wire.createRPC(util.wire.toAsync(f))}, 'uService']`. `routes.put("uService", { do: rpcStubPointingToN2_f })`

m2 is the argument list to the method call. This is because f() takes no args, and simply increments a pointer arg. So local.comm.send(m1, r1, (e, v)...) is actually `local.comm.send(args, remote_func, do nothing with callback)`

`local.comm.send(m, r, cb)`: call the remote function identified by r with arguments m, run cb(err, value) when remote side replies.

